Reasoning: The paper deals with geometric graphs and algorithms for computing them, which suggests that it belongs to the computational geometry (cs.CG) sub-category. The use of Well-Separated Pair Decomposition (WSPD) and the focus on pairwise disjoint balls suggests that it may also belong to the data structures (cs.DS) and discrete mathematics (cs.DM) sub-categories. The analysis of the number of edges in an imprecise $t$-spanner for a specific point set suggests that it may belong to the numerical analysis (cs.NA) sub-category. Finally, the use of geometric spanners and the focus on graph algorithms suggests that it may also belong to the graph theory (cs.GR) sub-category.
